## Purpose
Settings governs application-wide behavior and is the only feature that all other features are permitted to read from.
That asymmetric relationship creates unique engineering constraints. Incorrect settings implementation causes cross-feature regressions.
This rule encodes the contract of the settings system.

## Scope
Any file inside `lib/features/settings/` and any provider in `lib/shared/providers/` that exposes a setting value.

## Core Principles
- Settings are consumed by other features exclusively through shared providers in `lib/shared/providers/` — features never import from `lib/features/settings/` directly.
- Adding a new setting is an atomic operation: the setting schema, the persistence implementation, the shared provider, and the UI to modify it are all implemented together in the same commit.
- Settings are read-only from the perspective of all features except `settings/`. Only the settings feature may trigger a write to a setting.
- Settings must be persisted immediately on change — they are never held in memory and flushed later.
- Default values for all settings must be defined in one location, not scattered across call sites.

## DO
- Expose settings values through typed, named providers: `defaultDelimiterProvider`, `autosaveIntervalProvider`.
- Define all default values in a single `SettingsDefaults` class in `features/settings/domain/`.
- Validate settings values at write time — do not persist invalid values and silently fall back to defaults at read time.

## DON'T
- Import `lib/features/settings/` from any other feature. Use only the shared providers.
- Add a new setting without implementing its UI at the same time.
- Store a setting value as a global constant — settings must be user-configurable at runtime.

## NEVER
- Allow another feature to write to a setting directly — all writes go through the settings notifier.
- Remove a setting that is in use across features without migrating all consumers first.

## GOOD Example
```dart
// Correct: other features read settings via shared provider
// lib/shared/providers/settings_providers.dart
final defaultDelimiterProvider = Provider<String>((ref) {
  return ref.watch(settingsNotifierProvider).defaultDelimiter;
});

// Consumed in mapping feature
final delimiter = ref.watch(defaultDelimiterProvider);
```

## BAD Example
```dart
// Wrong: direct feature-to-feature import
import 'package:forkumentos/features/settings/domain/app_settings.dart';
final delimiter = AppSettings.instance.defaultDelimiter;
```

## Decision Rules
New application preference needed? → Add to schema, implement persistence, add shared provider, add UI — all atomically.
Feature needs to read a setting? → Use the shared provider in `lib/shared/providers/`. Never import `features/settings/` directly.
Feature needs to write a setting? → Surface this as an architectural question — only the settings feature writes settings.

## Conflict Resolution
`architecture_boundaries.mdc` normally prohibits cross-feature dependencies. This rule codifies the one deliberate exception: settings values are shared through providers, not through direct imports. `architecture_boundaries.mdc` governs the mechanism; this rule governs the contract.
